);

##############################################

Context("LimitedNumeric");

$a=random(2,10,1);
$b=random(2,5,1);
$c=random(2,5,1);
$d=random(2,5,1);

$ans=Compute($a-$b*(-$c)*$d);

##############################################

TEXT(beginproblem());

BEGIN_PGML

Evaluate the following.

    [`` [$a]-[$b](-[$c])[$d] =  ``]  [________]{$ans}


END_PGML

##############################################

BEGIN_PGML_SOLUTION

Since there is no operation symbol between [`[$b]`] and [`(-[$c])`], and between [`(-[$c])`] and [`[$d]`], it implies multiplication.

       [``
            \begin{aligned}[t]
           [$a]-[$b](-[$c])[$d] 
              &= [$a]-[$b] \cdot (-[$c]) \cdot [$d] \\
              &= [$a]-(-[$b*$c]) \cdot [$d] \\
              &= [$a]-(-[$b*$c*$d]) \\
              &= [$a]+[$b*$c*$d] \\
              & = [$ans] 
              \end{aligned}
        ``]

An easier way to do this problem is to treat the subtraction symbol between [`[$a]`] and [`[$b]`] as a negative symbol:


       [``
            \begin{aligned}[t]
           [$a]-[$b](-[$c])[$d] 
              &= [$a]+(-[$b]) \cdot (-[$c]) \cdot [$d] \\
              &= [$a]+[$b*$c] \cdot [$d] \\
              &= [$a]+[$b*$c*$d] \\
              & = [$ans] 
              \end{aligned}
        ``]

END_PGML_SOLUTION

